CHAPTER 3: METHODOLOGY
====================================================================

3.1 Introduction
This chapter describes the methodology adopted for the design, implementation, and evaluation of the Malware Image Recognition and Classification System. It explains the software development approach selected for the project, the machine learning model employed, the sequence of activities performed in each development phase, and the design artefacts used to guide implementation. The chapter also provides diagram-ready descriptions for the system architecture, process flow, activity sequence, and threat model so that the methodological structure of the project can be clearly communicated in formal academic presentation.

3.2 Software Development Method

3.2.1 Available Development Approaches
Several software development approaches were considered during the planning stage of the project. The Waterfall model provides clear sequential stages and strong documentation, but it is less adaptable when implementation changes are frequently required. The Prototyping model is suitable when interface refinement and user feedback are important. Agile and iterative approaches support repeated improvement, incremental delivery, and continuous verification.

3.2.2 Selected Development Model
For this project, an iterative prototyping approach was selected. This choice was appropriate because the system combines multiple technical domains, namely web application development, machine learning inference, malware image preprocessing, database interaction, and security-sensitive file handling. Such a system is unlikely to reach a stable and reliable state through a strictly linear process. Instead, it benefits from repeated refinement in response to runtime findings, classification behaviour, integration issues, and user-facing presentation requirements.

3.2.3 Justification for the Selected Method
The iterative prototyping model was selected for the following reasons:
- the machine learning output required repeated validation and interpretation
- the frontend and backend components had to be integrated incrementally
- system reliability needed improvement through continuous debugging and retesting
- security-related controls such as upload validation and CSRF protection required verification in practice
- confidence interpretation and malware category mapping required refinement after observing real outputs

Accordingly, the project methodology is best characterised as iterative, evaluation-driven, and prototype-oriented.

3.3 Selected Machine Learning Model and Justification

3.3.1 Selected Model
The machine learning component of the system uses MobileNetV2 as the primary image classification architecture. MobileNetV2 is a lightweight convolutional neural network designed to achieve strong classification performance while remaining computationally efficient.

3.3.2 Rationale for Model Selection
MobileNetV2 was selected for several academic and practical reasons. First, the project operates on malware image representations, which makes convolutional neural networks a natural choice due to their effectiveness in extracting spatial features from image data. Second, the project was developed and demonstrated in a local environment with moderate computational resources; therefore, a lightweight architecture was preferable to a significantly larger model. Third, the project required a model that could support both acceptable training performance and fast inference during live demonstration.

The use of MobileNetV2 is therefore justified by the following advantages:
- suitability for image-based classification problems
- efficient inference under constrained hardware resources
- compatibility with transfer learning workflows
- strong balance between performance and model size
- appropriateness for real-time or near-real-time local inference

3.3.3 Adaptation of the Model to the Project
Within this project, MobileNetV2 was adapted to classify malware image samples into 25 malware families derived from the MALIMG-style dataset. The classifier layer was modified to match the total number of classes, and the model was trained using a structured train-validation-test split. The trained model was later integrated into the web-based inference service.

3.4 Project Phases and Activities

3.4.1 Requirement Identification and Problem Analysis
The first phase of the project focused on understanding the problem domain. Malware binaries are difficult to interpret directly using raw byte sequences alone, particularly for non-specialist users. The project therefore aimed to transform malware-related files into image representations and apply a machine learning model to classify them into known malware families. During this phase, the system requirements for upload handling, visualization, classification, security, result presentation, and storage were identified.

3.4.2 Project Planning and Work Breakdown Structure
The project was organised into a structured sequence of work packages. Although a full graphical Gantt chart is not embedded in this draft, the project planning can be expressed as the following work breakdown structure:

1. Literature review and problem definition
2. Requirement identification and system planning
3. Dataset preparation and split verification
4. Preprocessing and model development
5. Web frontend implementation
6. API integration and inference workflow implementation
7. Database and session fallback support
8. Security hardening and reliability improvements
9. Validation-based calibration and threshold tuning
10. Testing, discussion, and documentation

This structure demonstrates that the project was managed through clear phases rather than ad hoc coding.

3.4.3 Dataset Preparation and Preprocessing
The dataset used in this project is a MALIMG-style malware image dataset organised into training, validation, and test partitions. The system supports 25 malware families. The preprocessing strategy included image resizing, grayscale-to-three-channel conversion for model compatibility, tensor conversion, and normalization using ImageNet statistics. A shared preprocessing configuration was implemented to ensure consistency across training, evaluation, testing, and inference.

3.4.4 Model Training and Validation
During the training phase, the model was trained on the training split and monitored using the validation split. The objective of this phase was to learn discriminative features for malware family classification while preventing overfitting through validation-based monitoring. The resulting model artefacts included trained weights, label mappings, and performance metrics.

3.4.5 Web System Design and Backend Integration
The project was implemented as a web-based prototype. The frontend was developed in PHP and is responsible for user interaction, upload control, conversion flow, and result display. The backend machine learning service was developed in Python using FastAPI. This phase involved integrating the PHP application with the ML API so that uploaded images could be analysed and the returned prediction could be displayed to the user.

3.4.6 Confidence Calibration and Threshold Selection
An important methodological refinement of the project was the treatment of confidence. Rather than relying solely on raw softmax output, the project extracted validation logits, fitted temperature scaling using validation data, and selected a decision threshold on the same validation set. This process improved the interpretability of confidence values and reduced the risk of presenting uncertain predictions as fully certain.

3.4.7 Interpretation Layer: Category and Severity Mapping
The trained classifier predicts malware family labels only. Category labels such as Trojan or Other Malware, as well as severity levels such as Low, Medium, and High, were introduced as an interpretation layer after prediction. This mapping was applied consistently across the supported MALIMG families so that the final result presented to the user remained interpretable and aligned with project objectives.

3.4.8 Testing and Iterative Refinement
Testing was performed continuously throughout development. Functional testing, security-related checks, result interpretation review, and interface validation all contributed to iterative refinement. Several issues, including session handling, database fallback behaviour, confidence interpretation, and category consistency, were identified and corrected during this phase.

