CHAPTER 4: SYSTEM DEVELOPMENT
====================================================================

4.1 Introduction
This chapter explains the development of the Malware Image Recognition and Classification System from a technical perspective. It covers the software frameworks and dependencies employed, the development environment, installation and configuration procedures, user interface design, system integration, source code management, solution evolution, and deployment configuration. The chapter demonstrates how the methodology described previously was translated into a functioning prototype.

4.2 Frameworks, Dependencies, Environment, Operating System, IDE, and Development Tools

4.2.1 Frontend and Web Layer
The web application layer was developed using PHP, HTML, and CSS. PHP was selected because it supports server-side request handling, file upload management, session management, and straightforward integration with local database services. HTML and CSS were used to design the web pages and result presentation interface.

4.2.2 Machine Learning Layer
The machine learning backend was implemented in Python. FastAPI was used to expose the trained classifier as an HTTP-based service. PyTorch and TorchVision were used to build and run the MobileNetV2 model. Pillow was used for image loading and preprocessing, while scikit-learn and NumPy supported evaluation and numerical operations.

4.2.3 Database Layer
MySQL/MariaDB was used as the persistent storage mechanism for analysis results. Where database storage was temporarily unavailable, session-based fallback was implemented to preserve workflow continuity.

4.2.4 Development Environment
The project was developed under Linux using Visual Studio Code as the main integrated development environment. Git and GitHub were used for version control and milestone management. A Python virtual environment was used to isolate machine learning dependencies. Runtime validation was supported through terminal-based testing, PHP error logs, database checks, and direct API inspection.

4.3 Installation, Setup, and Configuration

4.3.1 Installation Procedure
The local setup procedure can be summarised as follows:
1. Prepare the project in the local workspace.
2. Create and activate the Python virtual environment under the ML service directory.
3. Install the Python dependencies required by the ML service.
4. Ensure the dataset directories and model artefacts are present.
5. Ensure PHP is available for the frontend.
6. Ensure MySQL/MariaDB is available for database-backed result storage.
7. Launch the PHP and ML services.

4.3.2 Configuration Details
The prototype uses a local configuration in which:
- the PHP application runs at http://localhost:8000
- the ML service runs at http://127.0.0.1:5000
- model artefacts are loaded from the models directory
- uploads, sessions, and logs are maintained in local filesystem directories

Additional reliability features include health checks, startup scripts, local session hardening, and secure upload validation.

4.4 User Interface and User Experience Design
The user interface was designed for simplicity, clarity, and academic demonstration. The prototype follows a dark-themed visual style that emphasises the analysis result panel and the malware image preview. The workflow was intentionally kept short so that a user can move quickly from upload to classification result.

The principal interface goals were:
- provide a clear and linear analysis workflow
- present malware family and severity clearly
- show confidence in an understandable form
- support rapid use during live presentation
- ensure that errors are handled gracefully without confusing the user

4.5 Integration Between Frontend and Backend
The frontend and backend are integrated through an API-based communication model. The PHP layer accepts the uploaded image and forwards it to the ML service. The ML service performs inference and returns the prediction as JSON. The PHP layer then stores the result either in the database or, if necessary, in the session, before rendering the final result page.

This approach allows the system to remain modular. The PHP application is responsible for interaction and presentation, while the FastAPI service is responsible for classification logic.

4.6 Source Code Versioning and Repository Management
Version control was handled through Git, with GitHub used as the remote repository. The use of version control was especially important because the system underwent repeated refinement in both the frontend and ML service. Repository management enabled safe checkpointing of improvements such as confidence calibration, threshold tuning, mapping corrections, and reliability fixes.

4.7 Solution Evolution and Implementation Versions
The system evolved through multiple implementation stages. Important milestones included:
- initial web frontend and model integration
- correction of runtime and conversion errors
- database fallback support
- startup automation and health checking
- severity mapping enhancement
- confidence calibration using validation data
- threshold tuning using validation performance
- category consistency fixes across all MALIMG families

This incremental evolution reflects the chosen iterative development methodology.

4.8 Deployment Environment
The deployment environment is local and intended for development and academic demonstration. The deployed components consist of:
- local PHP application server
- local FastAPI inference service
- local MySQL/MariaDB database
- local file storage for uploads, logs, and sessions

This deployment model was selected because it offers simplicity, controllability, and suitability for offline academic use. However, it also means that the present prototype should be regarded as a local demonstrator rather than a production deployment.

4.9 Summary
This chapter has described the practical development of the system, including the technical stack, environment, setup, interface design, integration model, repository management, iterative improvements, and deployment configuration. The resulting system is a complete local prototype that integrates malware image preprocessing, model inference, secure request handling, and result presentation.

