5.2.3 User Acceptance and Output Evaluation
User-facing evaluation in this project is primarily concerned with the clarity and usefulness of the output. The results page displays the predicted malware family, interpreted category, severity level, confidence value, and the analysed image preview. This presentation format supports understandable and demonstrable output during evaluation.

Observed strengths include:
- clear end-to-end workflow
- readable result panel structure
- visible malware image preview
- more honest handling of uncertain predictions after calibration and threshold tuning

5.3 Results and Discussion
The trained model achieved strong overall classification performance on the dataset used in this study. The best validation accuracy was approximately 98.07%, while the final test accuracy was approximately 98.36%. The macro F1-score was approximately 94.40%, and the weighted F1-score was approximately 97.82%.

These findings suggest that the selected MobileNetV2 architecture is effective for malware family recognition on the prepared MALIMG-style dataset. The results support the feasibility of applying image-based deep learning techniques to malware family classification under the chosen problem setting.

At the same time, the project also revealed an important distinction between benchmark performance and real deployment behaviour. Although dataset-based performance is high, live uploaded or converted samples do not always produce equally high confidence. This indicates the presence of distributional differences between evaluation data and certain real inputs. To address this issue, the project introduced validation-based temperature scaling and a tuned decision threshold so that the reported confidence became more academically defensible.

Another important result concerns interpretability. Since the model predicts malware families rather than high-level categories or severity labels, an additional interpretation layer was needed. During implementation, inconsistencies in category mapping were identified and corrected, leading to a more coherent and policy-consistent final output.

5.4 Summary
This chapter has discussed the evaluation results of the project from functional, security-related, and interpretability perspectives. The system achieved strong classification performance, supported the required workflows, and provided a more trustworthy result interpretation through calibration and threshold tuning. Overall, the findings demonstrate that the project met its intended technical and academic objectives.

