CHAPTER 6: CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS
====================================================================

6.1 Introduction
This chapter presents the final conclusions of the project. It summarises the principal achievements, discusses how the objectives were fulfilled, identifies the main limitations of the present work, and offers recommendations for future improvement and broader practical extension.

6.2 Conclusion of the Project
The Malware Image Recognition and Classification System was successfully developed as a working academic prototype. The system can convert malware-related files into image representations, classify them into known malware families, assign interpretable category and severity labels, and present the final results through a web interface. The integration of the PHP frontend with the FastAPI-based machine learning backend resulted in a coherent end-to-end system rather than a standalone experimental model.

6.3 Discussion of Findings
The findings of this study indicate that MobileNetV2 is an appropriate classifier for the selected problem and dataset context. The model achieved strong validation and test performance, supporting the use of malware image representations for family-level classification. The study also demonstrated that confidence reporting requires careful treatment. By introducing calibration and threshold tuning, the project improved the honesty and reliability of result interpretation. Additionally, the work showed that category and severity presentation must be governed by a consistent interpretation policy to avoid contradictory outputs.

6.4 Achievement of Objectives
Objective 1: Develop a malware image classification prototype
This objective was achieved through the implementation of a complete web-based malware analysis workflow.

Objective 2: Classify malware images into known families
This objective was achieved by training and deploying a MobileNetV2 model supporting 25 malware families.

Objective 3: Provide interpretable results to the user
This objective was achieved by presenting family, category, severity, confidence, and image preview on the results page.

Objective 4: Improve confidence reliability
This objective was achieved through validation-logit extraction, temperature scaling, and threshold tuning.

Objective 5: Maintain prototype reliability during demonstration
This objective was achieved through startup scripts, health checks, secure upload handling, and session fallback support.

6.5 Limitations
The project is subject to several limitations:
1. the current deployment is local and demonstration-oriented
2. severity labels are policy-based and not learned from behavioural ground truth
3. live uploaded samples may differ from the validation distribution
4. the interpretation layer depends on the quality of the family mapping policy
5. the prototype has not yet been extended to scalable production deployment
6. local service configuration remains a practical dependency for full operation

6.6 Recommendations for Future Work
Future improvements should include:
1. training on a larger and more diverse malware dataset
2. introducing unknown or out-of-distribution detection
3. refining severity assignment using cited malware taxonomy sources
4. adding reliability diagrams and confusion matrices to the evaluation chapter
5. improving the frontend with richer visual analytics
6. automating database setup and schema management
7. extending the system toward malware behaviour tagging or multi-label analysis
8. exploring containerized or cloud deployment strategies

6.7 Future Expansion
Potential later enhancements include drag-and-drop upload, bulk analysis, downloadable reports, model comparison dashboards, role-based access control, and cloud-hosted storage and inference services.

6.8 Commercialization Potential
Although the current implementation is an academic prototype, the concept has practical potential for educational laboratories, malware research support environments, cyber security training platforms, and lightweight malware triage systems. Any move toward commercialization would require stronger production security, broader validation, scalable deployment architecture, and operational monitoring.

6.9 Final Summary
In summary, the project demonstrates that malware image classification can be implemented as a practical and interpretable prototype by combining web technologies, machine learning inference, confidence calibration, and structured result presentation. The prototype achieved its main objectives and provides a solid foundation for further academic and technical development.
